sec.p:
The taxonomy in this genus is complex since morphologically they are similar, including the male genitalia ( Chopard, 1961 ), the separation of species by morphological methods is laborious, the song is necessary for a positive identification ( Weissman & Gray, 2019 ). The identity of North American species has been studied and their genetic and acoustic limits have been established ( Weissman & Gray, 2019 ;
Gray et al ., 2020
), but for Central and South America the separation and delimitation of the species has not been possible, with methods similar to those used with North American taxa. On the contrary, the Central and South American species were described a long time ago, with specimens mostly without precise localities, or based on females, and several of the species are missing type specimens, making it even more difficult to identify species. The data for the type specimens of the Gryllus species
discussed below are given by
Hollier et al . (2013)
.
